I'm new to networking, and new to NAMEDROPPERS, so I may be asking an old
question here, but could someone tell me more about the IN-ADDR.ARPA domain?
All I know about it is the info in RFC1034 ("its role is to translate
from network or host numbers to names").  I'm curious.  How does this work?
How is it kept up when domain administrators are free to name new nodes?
I'm sure it wouldn't know to resolve 192.35.51.6 to LAOTSE.CARLETON.EDU,
since this is a PC we are using for TCP/IP testing, which has had no contact
with the net at large.

Also, why is the NIC still in the `temporary' ARPA domain?  Have they, like
compassionate disciples of the Buddha, vowed to pass last into enlightenment?
Or do they simply not know which domain they belong in?

Any info on my serious or my semi-serious question (you can guess which
is which, I hope) would be appreciated.

				Dave Diehl
				Student Programmer
				(DIEHLD@CARLETON.EDU)
				...!umn-cs!stolaf!ccnfld!diehld

